1
00:00:04,700 --> 00:00:07,919
As part of your bivariate exploration,

2
00:00:07,919 --> 00:00:11,719
you might be interested in relationships between lots of variables.

3
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:15,570
You could explore these relationships two variables at a time,

4
00:00:15,570 --> 00:00:18,480
but there are other techniques besides multi-variate plots to

5
00:00:18,480 --> 00:00:21,964
explore multiple pairwise relationships at the same time.

6
00:00:21,964 --> 00:00:23,625
In a plot matrix,

7
00:00:23,625 --> 00:00:25,804
a grid of plots is generated.

8
00:00:25,804 --> 00:00:31,000
Unlike a faceted plot where each subplot is based on one subset of the data,

9
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,698
each subplot in a plot matrix is based on the whole data,

10
00:00:34,698 --> 00:00:37,820
but with two different variables on the axes.

11
00:00:37,820 --> 00:00:41,659
Each row and column corresponds with one variable.

12
00:00:41,659 --> 00:00:47,184
For example, this plot shows the relationship between sugars and fats.

13
00:00:47,185 --> 00:00:51,745
Along the diagonal, the row variable and column variable match up.

14
00:00:51,744 --> 00:00:57,500
A univariate plot of each variable is usually placed along this diagonal line.

15
00:00:57,500 --> 00:00:59,929
A plot matrix is good for getting

16
00:00:59,929 --> 00:01:03,829
a broad overview of pairwise relationships between variables.

17
00:01:03,829 --> 00:01:07,569
Considering that the size of each subplot will be fairly small,

18
00:01:07,569 --> 00:01:09,229
a plot matrix is best as

19
00:01:09,230 --> 00:01:13,805
an initial exploratory tool to lead you to points of further interest.

20
00:01:13,805 --> 00:01:16,685
You should follow up a plot matrix by generating

21
00:01:16,685 --> 00:01:20,225
additional plots of specific variable sets on their own.

22
00:01:20,224 --> 00:01:22,879
We can also adapt heatmaps to depict

23
00:01:22,879 --> 00:01:26,114
the pairwise correlations between variables in our data.

24
00:01:26,114 --> 00:01:28,039
Like the plot matrix,

25
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:31,425
each row and column corresponds with a single variable.

26
00:01:31,424 --> 00:01:34,759
The value and color depicted in each cell is

27
00:01:34,760 --> 00:01:38,880
the correlation between the corresponding row and column variables.

28
00:01:38,879 --> 00:01:41,449
This is another good summary option for

29
00:01:41,450 --> 00:01:44,280
exploration when starting with a lot of variables.

